diff:1670646274:1670517738:=53,69c53%0a%3c #foxbegin 221210-042434-508080#%0a%3c (:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a%3c !!!How Cued Speech Can Be Helpful For Those Without Hearing Impairments %0a%3c -> - manu%0a%3c -> [-09.12.2022 - 20:24-]%0a%3c >>rfloat%3c%3c   %0a%3c (:if1 authgroup @tas:)%0a%3c {[foxdelrange button 221210-042434-508080 {$FullName} ]}%0a%3c (:if1end:)%0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c (:div1end:) %0a%3c >>messageitem%3c%3c %0a%3c Although it was created for people who are hearing impaired, cued speech is actually well suited to help many students with special needs, regardless of their hearing status. For people with speech problems such as apraxia or a stutter, cued speech can help “build…neurological patterns in the brain” which has been shown to improve speech. For students with autism or other pervasive developmental disorders, Cued Speech allows “students to perceive and process speech through their sense of vision”, which may be preferred and more helpful in many cases. The integration of multiple senses has been beneficial for many of these students.%0a%3c %0a%3c https://commons.emich.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?referer=&httpsredir=1&article=1127&context=honors%0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c #foxend 221210-042434-508080#%0a---%0a> %0a
